    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-17T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-17T02:00:00-05:00" n="385"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d385">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94116/5: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="#p_GPB1" type="from"
                            >Gilbert</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-17T08:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 17, 1932—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. Consulate’s 83, February 14, 3 p.m. Following is the full text of a telegram
                    dated February 15 received by the Japanese delegation and given to <persName
                        corresp="#p_DSE1">Drummond</persName> for circulation: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“On receipt of a protest from <persName corresp="#p_SSJH1">Sir John Hope
                                Simpson</persName> against the aerial bombardment of the flood
                            relief refugee camp on February 5th, 6th and 7th, the Japanese Consul
                            General at once communicated with the naval authorities who asked him to
                            express their deep regret for this incident. It was due they said to a
                            deplorable mistake: the refugee camp was close to the entrenchments and
                            other military works that the Chinese were constructing, which the
                            Japanese aircraft had orders to destroy, and as the camp was also
                            surrounded by barbed wire they dropped bombs on it. The naval
                            authorities greatly regretted that they were not informed of the facts
                            until February 10, several days after the bombing, as prompt
                            representations might have prevented these distressing incidents.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GPB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
